Igor pointed out my misreading of the question.

The question I answered was, &quot;Would it be worth developing a filter for
the ARCWriterProcessor so only blessed content types made it into the
archive.&quot;

Rather, the question asks about developing a filter that somehow, before
we made the request (or mid-request), makes a ruling on whether the HTTP
GET should proceed. There&#39;s no attachment point for such a filter in the
current processing model. To allow for such an attachment point, we
would need to do something like insert into our HTTP Fetcher a HTTP HEAD
request, examine the HTTP HEAD return, and if it passes the proposed
filter test, only then go ahead and HTTP GET.

Our general thinking on such a model is that the HTTP HEAD, in the
scheme of things, is probably just as expensive as a HTTP GET so little
point in first doing a HTTP HEAD request. We should probably add this
facility at some stage, but until we do, it won&#39;t be possible to write
such as the suggested filter.

Is this what you were thinking Ansi?

Yours,
St.Ack



